@article{ WOS:001696532400003,
Author = {Yang, Yongzheng and Liao, Kun and Wang, Yufei and Hu, Xiaoyong and Gong,
   Qihuang},
Title = {Optical Machine Learning Based on Thin-Film Lithium Niobate (Invited)},
Journal = {ACTA OPTICA SINICA},
Year = {2026},
Volume = {46},
Number = {3},
Month = {FEB},
Abstract = {Significance With the exponential growth in computing power demand
   driven by artificial intelligence, electronic chips are facing severe
   challenges as Moore's Law approaches its physical limits. Optical
   computing, leveraging the inherent advantages of light-speed
   propagation, parallel processing, and low energy consumption, is
   regarded as a key technology to break through the computing bottleneck
   and potentially bring disruptive changes. The thin-film lithium niobate
   (TFLN) integrated photonic platform, notable for its excellent
   electro-optic effect and low optical loss, demonstrates great potential
   for building high-performance photonic computing systems. Compared to
   traditional platforms of silicon, indium phosphide, and gallium
   arsenide, TFLN offers superior performance in modulation bandwidth,
   drive voltage, and transmission loss, gradually becoming an ideal
   platform for building high-speed, low-power programmable photonic
   processors. Achieving high-performance TFLN photonic integrated systems
   faces serious challenges: efficiently designing and optimizing the
   fundamental functional units. Traditional design methods, often reliant
   on parameter scanning and physics-intuition-based forward design,
   struggle to balance compactness, high performance, and manufacturing
   tolerance effectively. Machine learning technology addresses this
   bottleneck through inverse design, efficiently mapping the complex
   relationship between device parameters and optical responses, thereby
   significantly improving device optimization efficiency. Simultaneously,
   the TFLN platform has emerged as an ideal vehicle for implementing
   optical neural networks. Its high electro-optic coefficient enables
   low-power, high-bandwidth linear computing units, facilitating
   reconfigurable matrix computation cores. Its second-order nonlinear
   effects provide a physical basis for implementing nonlinear activation
   functions. Combined with wavelength and time multiplexing techniques,
   TFLN-based optical neural networks have demonstrated potential for
   high-speed, energy-efficient applications in tasks like image
   classification, forming a closed-loop development path from intelligent
   device design to in-situ optical intelligent computing and advancing
   optical computing towards large-scale, reconfigurable systems. Progress
   In this paper, we focus on the TFLN intelligent optical computing
   platform, systematically organizing and elaborating on two cutting-edge
   directions of the integration between machine learning and TFLN.
   Specifically, the review covers 1) the inverse design of TFLN photonic
   integrated devices assisted by artificial intelligence algorithms, and
   2) neural network computing acceleration via the TFLN photonic platform.
   In the domain of integrated devices, inverse design methods have
   substantially advanced the performance boundaries of fundamental TFLN
   components. Heuristic algorithms, the adjoint method and deep learning
   have been successfully implemented on TFLN coupling devices, enabling
   the realization of power splitters with low insertion loss and large
   bandwidth, as well as grating couplers with high coupling efficiency, as
   shown in Fig. 1. These inverse design approaches have also been extended
   to wavelength control devices, including wavelength demultiplexers,
   arrayed waveguide gratings, reflectors, and nonlinear dispersion
   engineering structures, as shown in Fig. 2. Furthermore, the performance
   of mode-modulated devices like mode multiplexers and mode converters has
   also been enhanced, as shown in Fig. 3.
   These high-performance devices lay a solid foundation for constructing
   high-density, low-loss optical neural networks. As for integrated
   systems, the TFLN platform already supports the implementation of
   various optical neural network architectures, covering three main types:
   spatial division, time division, and multi-dimensional multiplexing. For
   spatial division architectures, the core advantage of multi-space
   channel architectures lies in their high parallelism and high fidelity
   (Fig. 4). Time-division multiplexing architectures leverage high-speed
   electro-optic modulators to achieve real-time weight updates with
   minimal hardware footprint, as shown in Fig. 5. Multi-dimensional
   multiplexing architecture optical neural networks further enhance
   parallelism, enabling multiplicative growth in computational scale (Fig.
   6). Nonlinear computation represents a critical challenge in optical
   neural networks. Leveraging its high second-order nonlinear coefficient,
   the TFLN platform enables all-optical nonlinear activation functions via
   periodically poled lithium niobate (PPLN) waveguides, which benefit from
   ultra-short response times, making them particularly suitable for
   high-speed inference in feedforward neural networks (Fig. 7). The TFLN
   platform is gradually being embedded into heterogeneous
   photonic-electronic systems. Figure 8 shows the applications of
   photonic-assisted computing: edge feature extraction for image
   processing, high-performance analog-to-digital conversion for photonic
   computing and photonic ray tracing cores for ray-box intersection tests
   in ray tracing acceleration. Conclusions and Prospects This paper
   systematically reviews current research progress in optimization of TFLN
   integrated devices using inverse design methods and architectural
   solutions for optical neural networks based on this platform. The rapid
   development of TFLN photonic integration platforms still faces
   fundamental challenges in technical and systematic schemes. In inverse
   design, future work will fuse multiple algorithms and embed intrinsic
   material properties into artificial intelligence models to boost
   optimization. For optical neural networks, the critical breakthroughs
   lie in nanostructure-enhanced nonlinearities and in fully exploiting
   multiplexing across mode, time, space and wavelength to create
   higher-dimensional computing architectures. As for system, we should
   focus on optimizing TFLN photonic-electronic computing units through
   heterogeneous integration technologies and developing hardware-aware
   model compression techniques alongside specialized training strategies.
   From an industrialization perspective, there is a need to promote the
   standardization of micro-nano fabrication processes, establish
   comprehensive process design kits, and achieve high-density
   photonic-electronic integration through advanced packaging and interface
   technologies. TFLN-based optical machine learning has the potential to
   mature into a commercial technology, offering a new route to break
   electronic computing bottlenecks and support next-generation intelligent
   computing systems.},
Type = {Article},
Affiliation = {Liao, K; Hu, XY (Corresponding Author), Peking Univ, Sch Phys, State Key Lab Mesoscop Phys, Beijing 100871, Peoples R China.
   Liao, K; Hu, XY (Corresponding Author), Peking Univ, Sch Phys, Dept Phys, Beijing 100871, Peoples R China.
