   Pooja P. and Selvaraj, Manickam and Assiri, Mohammed A. and Kulkarni,
   Sachin V. and Sutar, Santosh S. and Amate, Rutuja U. and Jeon, Chan-Wook
   and Dongale, Tukaram D. and Shah, Prashant P.},
Title = {From data to device: Machine learning-driven optimization, predictions,
   and experimental insights for engineering high-performance MnO2
   supercapacitors},
Journal = {COLLOIDS AND SURFACES A-PHYSICOCHEMICAL AND ENGINEERING ASPECTS},
Year = {2025},
Volume = {727},
Number = {3},
Month = {DEC 20},
Abstract = {Manganese dioxide (MnO2) has garnered significant interest as a
   promising electrode material for super-capacitors (SCs). However,
   traditional experimental methods for optimizing MnO2-based SCs are often
   time intensive and limited in addressing key performance bottlenecks. To
   overcome these challenges, we employed machine learning (ML) techniques
   to identify optimal synthesis, fabrication, and electrochemical testing
   conditions for MnO2 SCs. A comprehensive dataset comprising
   approximately 5000 property entries was compiled from peer-reviewed
   publications. Using Classification and Regression Tree (CART) analysis,
   we extracted interpretable decision rules and assessed the impact of
   various input features on key performance metrics of MnO2 SCs (specific
   capacitance, cyclic stability, and capacitance retention). Feature
   importance scores were evaluated, and predictive models were developed
   using multiple ML algorithms. Herein, the random forest model exhibited
   the highest predictive accuracy. The ML insights were validated
   experimentally by fabricating MnO2 electrodes guided by CART-optimized
   conditions. The resulting MnO2 SC achieved a specific capacitance of 498
   F/g, excellent cyclic stability over 10,000 cycles with 84.12 \%
   capacitance retention, and a coulombic efficiency of 95.52 \%. This
   study demonstrates the effectiveness of data-driven approaches in
   predicting and optimizing the performance of MnO2-based SCs, offering a
   robust framework for accelerating the design of energy storage devices.},
